get.description:
When streaming a run the outputs of the run will be streamed back to the consumer as they are created.

Start with an empty outputs object:

```ts
let outputs: Record<string, any> = {};
```

And connect to the stream

```js
const sse = new EventSource("https://api.wordware.ai/v1/runs/123/stream?token=567");
```

#### Output events

When you receive an `"outputs"` event

```
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: text/event-stream

event: outputs
data: {
  "type": "outputs",
  "outputs": {
    "my_js_code": {
      "logs": "Hello",
      "output": "World"
    }
  }
}
```

replace the current outputs with the outputs in the event

```js
sse.addEventListener("outputs", (e) => {
  const data = JSON.parse(e.data);
  outputs = data.outputs;
});
```

#### Value events

When you receive a `"value"` event

```
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: text/event-stream

event: value
data: {
  "type": "value",
  "path": "my_structured_generation.greeting",
  "value": "Hi there"
}
```

set the output value at the given `path` to the provided value. A great way to set the value for nested values is [dot-prop](https://www.npmjs.com/package/dot-prop)

```js
import { setProperty } from "dot-prop";

sse.addEventListener("value", (e) => {
  const data = JSON.parse(e.data);
  setProperty(outputs, data.path, data.value);
});
```

#### Text delta events

When you receive a `"delta"` event

```
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: text/event-stream

event: value
data: {
  "type": "delta",
  "path": "my_structured_generation.greeting",
  "delta": {
    "type": "text",
    "value": "Howdy "
  }
}
```

append the value in `delta.value` to the output value at the given `path`. A great way to set the value for nested values is [dot-prop](https://www.npmjs.com/package/dot-prop)

```js
import { setProperty, getProperty } from "dot-prop";

sse.addEventListener("delta", (e) => {
  const data = JSON.parse(e.data);
  const { delta } = data;

  if (delta.type !== "text") {
    // non text deltas are not yet supported
    return;
  }

  const outputValue = getProperty(outputs, data.path, "");

  setProperty(outputs, data.path, outputValue + delta.value);
});
```

#### Status events

When you receive a `"status"` event

```
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: text/event-stream

event: status
data: {
  "type": "status",
  "status": "cancelled"
}
```

you may act accoridnly to the value of `status`:

- `running`: The run is in a running state and more events are expected.
- `completed`: the run has completed successfully and no further events are expected. The event stream **MUST** be closed. This is a terminal state.
- `failed`: the run has failed to run and no further events are expected. The event stream **MUST** be closed. This is a terminal state.
- `cancelled`: the run was cancelled on request of the user. No further events are expected. The event stream **MUST** be closed. This is a terminal state.
- `suspended`: The run is suspended, awaiting the result of a callback. No events are expected until the callback is submitted.

```js
sse.addEventListener("status", (e) => {
  const data = JSON.parse(e.data);

  switch(data.status) {
    case: "completed":
      sse.close();
      break;
    case: "failed":
      sse.close();
      break;
    case: "cancelled":
      sse.close();
      break;
    default:
      // do nothing
  }
});
```

#### Ping events

When you receive a `"ping"` event

```
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: text/event-stream

event: ping
data: {
  "type": "ping"
}
```

you may ignore it completely by not registering an event listener.
